This article is about an executive order issued by President Barack Obama in September 2014, which focuses on combating antibiotic-resistant bacteria. The order acknowledges that antibiotics have saved millions of lives but highlights the rising threat of antibiotic-resistant bacteria to public health and the economy. The order calls for a strategic and coordinated effort involving various stakeholders, including governments, academia, industry, healthcare providers, and the agricultural community. The order establishes a Task Force for Combating Antibiotic-Resistant Bacteria, co-chaired by the Secretaries of Defense, Agriculture, and Health and Human Services (HHS). The Task Force is responsible for developing and implementing federal government policies to combat antibiotic-resistant bacteria. The order also establishes a Presidential Advisory Council on Combating Antibiotic-Resistant Bacteria, which provides advice and recommendations to the Secretary of HHS. The order emphasizes the need for improved antibiotic stewardship in healthcare facilities, as well as the development of new antibiotics and diagnostics. It also promotes international cooperation in combating antibiotic-resistant bacteria. The order is to be implemented in accordance with applicable law and subject to the availability of appropriations.